SIMPLE: glance
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Glance
<hw>Glance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to D.
<ets>glans</ets> luster, brightness, G. <ets>glanz</ets>, Sw.
<ets>glans</ets>, D. <ets>glands</ets> brightness, glimpse. Cf.
<er>Gleen</er>, <er>Glint</er>, <er>Glitter</er>, and <er>Glance</er> a
mineral.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A sudden flash of light or splendor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Swift as the lightning <qex>glance</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A quick cast of the eyes; a quick or a casual look;
a swift survey; a glimpse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dart not scornful <qex>glances</qex> from those eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An incidental or passing thought or
allusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How fleet is a <qex>glance</qex> of the mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A name given to some sulphides,
mostly dark-colored, which have a brilliant metallic luster, as the
sulphide of copper, called <xex>copper glance</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Glance coal</b></col>, <cd>anthracite; a mineral composed
chiefly of carbon.</cd> -- <col><b>Glance cobalt</b></col>,
<cd>cobaltite, or gray cobalt.</cd> -- <col><b>Glance copper</b></col>,
<cd>chalcocite.</cd> -- <col><b>Glance wood</b></col>, <cd>a hard wood
grown in Cuba, and used for gauging instruments, carpenters' rules,
etc.</cd> <au>McElrath.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glance</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Glance
<hw>Glance</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Glanced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Glancing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
shoot or emit a flash of light; to shine; to flash.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From art, from nature, from the schools,⟦br⟧
Let random influences <qex>glance</qex>,⟦br⟧
Like light in many a shivered lance,⟦br⟧
That breaks about the dappled pools.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strike and fly off in an oblique direction; to
dart aside. ⟦rdquo⟧Your arrow hath <xex>glanced</xex>⟦rdquo⟧.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On me the curse aslope⟦br⟧
<qex>Glanced</qex> on the ground.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To look with a sudden, rapid cast of the eye; to
snatch a momentary or hasty view.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The poet's eye, in a fine frenzy rolling,⟦br⟧
Doth <qex>glance</qex> from heaven to earth, from earth to heaven.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make an incidental or passing reflection; to
allude; to hint; -- often with <xex>at</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wherein obscurely⟦br⟧
Caesar's ambition shall be <qex>glanced</qex> at.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>glanced</qex> at a certain reverend doctor.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To move quickly, appearing and disappearing rapidly;
to be visible only for an instant at a time; to move interruptedly; to
twinkle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And all along the forum and up the sacred seat,⟦br⟧
His vulture eye pursued the trip of those small <qex>glancing</qex>
feet.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glance</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Glance
<hw>Glance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shoot
or dart suddenly or obliquely; to cast for a moment; <as>as, to
<ex>glance</ex> the eye</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hint at; to touch lightly or briefly.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In company I often <qex>glanced</qex> it.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glancing</ent>⟦br⟧
